{"title_page": "Broadway Centrum", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name                = Broadway Centrum\n| alternate_names     = {{ubl|GMA Broadway Centrum {{nobr|{{small|(1987\u20132012)}}}}|TV5 Broadway Centrum {{nobr|{{small|(2009\u20132013)}}}}|ABS-CBN Broadway Centrum|{{nobr|{{small|(2009-present)}}}}\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|14.611813|121.032245|display=inline}}\n| building_type       = Television studios\n| location            = [[New Manila]], [[Quezon City]]\n| address             = Aurora Boulevard cor. Broadway Avenue, Quezon City\n| owner               = {{ubl|[[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network]] {{small|(1987\u20132012)}}|[[Megaworld Corporation]] {{small|(2012\u20132018)}}}}\n[[Simone Cruz Network Corporation]] {{small|(2030-present)}}}}\n| current_tenants     =  \n| inauguration_date   = 1987\n}}\n\n'''Broadway Centrum''' was a [[television studio]] complex located in the [[New Manila]] district of [[Quezon City]] at Aurora Boulevard cor. Broadway (formerly Do\u00f1a Juana Rodriguez) Avenue, Quezon City. It is currently owned by the Empire East Land Holdings, a subsidiary of [[Megaworld Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Marlon Santeco |url=http://www.empireeastrealproperties.com/promos--updates |title=Empire East Land Holdings, Inc. Megaworld Central Properties, Inc. - Promos & Updates |publisher=Empireeastrealproperties.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref> It was previously owned by [[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network]].\n\nSince its opening, numerous television series have been broadcast live or taped at the facility, including many shows not broadcast on [[GMA Network]]. The complex houses two main studios \u2013 the ''Eastside'' and the ''Westside'' Theaters.\n\nIt is a former studio of the longest-running noontime show in the Philippines, ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'', which lasted for 23 years.\n\n==History==\n\nThe complex was inaugurated to usher [[GMA Network]]'s broadcast in stereovision. In 1987, it served as the live studio of variety shows ''[[Lunch Date]]'', ''[[That's Entertainment (TV program)|That's Entertainment]]'', ''[[Vilma (Philippine TV program)|Vilma!]]'' and ''[[GMA Supershow]]''. In 1995, GMA Network Inc. constructed the second studio within the Broadway Centrum by renovating the Eastside Theater & renamed as \"TAPE Studio, GMA Broadway Studio\" that can accommodate 400 studio audiences for its noontime show ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/599462/Broadway-Centrum-Complex |title=Broadway Centrum - Quezon City |publisher=Wikimapia.org |date= |accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/entertainment/entertainment/view/20100930-295268/Complete-creative-freedom-in-TV5-shows |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306121032/http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/entertainment/entertainment/view/20100930-295268/Complete-creative-freedom-in-TV5-shows |archivedate=2014-03-06 }}</ref>\n\n===Eat Bulaga era===\nThe Eastside Studios of the Broadway Centrum was the main home of the longest-running noontime show when TAPE Inc. constructed this studio and had its first broadcast here on September 16, 1995. From January 1 to March 5, 2010, ''Eat Bulaga!'' temporarily used the Westside Studios while the TAPE Studios was being renovated at that time. ''[[Diz Iz It!]]'' was the last GMA show that used the Westside Studios of Broadway Centrum in 2010. In the same year, the Westside Studios of Broadway Centrum did not have its tenants anymore for GMA Network because some of the network's shows migrated to their very own GMA Network Studios, while TV5 (now [[5 (TV channel)|5]]) leased and revived the Westside Studios with a new and bigger format. The site was owned by GMA Network and also shared with TV5. ''[[The Ryzza Mae Show]]'' was the last GMA show that used the Eastside Studios of the Broadway Centrum in 2013.\n\n===2011\u20132018===\nBoth Studios of the Broadway Centrum were active during that time, the Westside being leased by TV5 and was used for TV shows of the TV5 Entertainment Group such as ''[[Face to Face (talk show)|Face to Face]]'', ''[[The Jose and Wally Show Starring Vic Sotto]]'', ''[[P.O.5]]'', ''Star Factor'', ''[[Hey It's Saberdey!]]'' and ''[[Artista Academy]]'' and others, while the Eastside Studio was used by the longest-running variety show ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' and daily morning talk show ''[[The Ryzza Mae Show]]''.\n\nIn 2012, the Empire East Land Holdings, a subsidiary of [[Megaworld Corporation]] bought the Broadway Centrum to develop a residential condominium and a lifestyle mall at the site of the studio.<ref name=\"megawordunit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/364996/money/companies/megaworld-unit-empire-east-to-spend-p25b-to-buy-more-land-fund-projects |title=Megaworld unit Empire East to spend P25B to buy more land, fund projects &#124; Money &#124; GMA News Online |publisher=Gmanetwork.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"empireeastbroadway\">{{cite web|author=ABS-CBNnews.com |url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/06/10/14/empire-east-develop-broadway-centrum-property |title=Empire East to develop Broadway Centrum property |publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=2016-01-25 |accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"abandonedfactory\">{{cite web |last=Angela |first=Krista |url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/88767/empire-east-acquiring-abandoned-factory-to-build-new-township-bigger-than-eastwood-city |title=Empire East acquiring abandoned factory to build new township bigger than Eastwood City |publisher=Interaksyon.com |date=2014-06-10 |accessdate=2016-01-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724091910/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/88767/empire-east-acquiring-abandoned-factory-to-build-new-township-bigger-than-eastwood-city# |archive-date=2015-07-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn March 2014, TV5 ended its lease agreement at the Broadway Centrum, particularly at the Westside Studio as an alternate studio of the network as TV5 moved to [[TV5 Media Center]] in Reliance, [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmedia.com.ph/tv5-media-center-groundbreaking-coverage/|title=TV5 Media Center Groundbreaking Coverage|publisher=New Media Philippines|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2013/05/20/944102/kapatid-networks-new-home|title=Kapatid network\u2019s new home|publisher=PhilStar.Com|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://n5e.interaksyon.com/top/4EA1A901A12646E/1001/bagong-tahanan-ng-tv5-sa-mandaluyong-silipin |title=Bagong Tahanan ng TV5 sa Mandaluyong, Silipin |publisher=News5 Everywhere |accessdate=21 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224111513/http://n5e.interaksyon.com/top/4EA1A901A12646E/1001/bagong-tahanan-ng-tv5-sa-mandaluyong-silipin |archivedate=24 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe Broadway Centrum became a landmark once again thanks to the popularity of the [[AlDub]] loveteam in Eat Bulaga's segment, ''[[Kalyeserye]]'' where some memorable moments were set at the Broadway.\n\n===Demise and fate===\nOn December 7, 2018, the Broadway Centrum finally ended its long 31-year run as ''Eat Bulaga!'' broadcast its last episode there and, since December 8, 2018, has moved to their new state-of-the-art studio, the [[APT Studios]], located in [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], thus ending their 23-year tenure at the old studio.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anarcon |first1=James Patrick |title=Eat Bulaga looks back on RPN-9, ABS-CBN days as it transfers to new studio |url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/28916/eat-bulaga-looks-back-on-rpn-9-abs-cbn-days-as-it-transfers-to-new-studio |website=PEP.ph |accessdate=6 January 2019 |date=8 December 2018}}</ref> It is set to be demolished and redeveloped into a high-rise condominium and a mall complex which will be built by Empire East Land Holdings, the 1.7 hectare property's new owners.And Will Be Owned By Simone Cruz Network Corp In 2030 <ref name=\"megawordunit\" /><ref name=\"empireeastbroadway\" /><ref name=\"abandonedfactory\" />\n''\n\n==Shows produced at Broadway Centrum==\nBelow is a partial list of programs that have taped episodes at the studios.\n{{Div col}}\n*''[[Artista Academy]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Beh Bote Nga]]'' (1999\u20132000)\n*''Bitoys Adventures In Bilibkaba'' (1998\u20132000)\n*''[[Born to Be a Star (TV series)|Born to Be a Star]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Bubble Gang]]'' (1995\u20132000)\n*''D.A.T.S.'' (1997\u20131999)\n*''[[Digital LG Quiz]]'' (1999\u20132004)\n*''[[Diz Iz It!]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' (1995\u20132018)\n*''[[Face to Face (talk show)|Face to Face]]'' (2010\u20132013)\n*''[[GMA Supershow]]'' (1987\u20131997)\n*''[[GoBingo]]'' (1996\u20131999)\n*''Guwapings Live!'' (1992)\n*''[[HAPPinas Happy Hour]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Happy Truck HAPPinas]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Hey It's Saberdey!]]'' (2011\u20132012)\n*''[[It's Showtime (variety show)|It's Showtime]]'' (2012-present)\n*''Jamming'' (1999-2000)\n*''[[Katok Mga Misis!]]'' (1995\u20131997)\n*''Killer Karaoke: Pinoy Naman'' (2013\u20132014)\n*''[[Lunch Date]]'' (1987\u20131993)\n*''[[Martin After Dark]]'' (1988\u20131993)\n*''[[Move It: Clash of the Streetdancers|Move It!]]'' (2015)\n*''Mixed N.U.T.S.: Numerong Unong Terrific Show'' (1994\u20131997)\n*''Oooops With Wendell & Antonio'' (1997\u20131998)\n*''[[P.O.5]]'' (2010\u20132011)\n*''[[Rising Stars Philippines]]'' (2015)\n*''[[SST: Salo-Salo Together|Salo-Salo Together (SST)]]'' (1993\u20131995)\n''[[It's Showtime (variety show)|It's Showtime]]'' (2012-present)\n*''[[SOP (TV program)|SOP]]'' (1997\u20132000)\n*''Shades'' (1987\u20131988)\n*''[[Showbiz Central]]'' (2007\u20132012)\n*''Show & Tell'' (1994\u20131995)\n*''[[StarStruck (Filipino TV series)|StarStruck]]'' (2003\u20132007, 2009\u20132010)\n*''Star Factor'' (2010)\n*''[[Sunday Funday (TV program)|Sunday Funday]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Talentadong Pinoy]]'' (2008\u20132013, 2014)\n*''Tanghalan ng Kampeon'' (1989\u20131994)\n*''[[That's Entertainment (TV series)|That's Entertainment]]'' (1987\u20131996)\n*''[[The 700 Club|The 700 Club Asia]]'' (1995\u20132000)\n*''[[The Jose and Wally Show Starring Vic Sotto]]'' (2011\u20132012)\n*''[[The Ryzza Mae Show]]'' (2013\u20132015)\n*''[[Tok! Tok! Tok! Isang Milyon Pasok!]]'' (2007\u20132009)\n*''[[S-Files]]'' (1998\u20132007)\n*''[[Vilma!]]'' (1987\u20131995)\n*''[[Walang Tulugan with the Master Showman]]'' (1997\u20132010)\n*''What Went Wrong'' (1996\u20131999)\n*''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (Philippine game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' (2009\u20132015)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nBroadway Centrum, for the following movies, was usually used for taping or shooting:  \n\n===''Sige Ihataw Mo'' (1993)===\nThe movie is set in Westside Studios, where some of the pivotal scenes were shot.  It is also headlined by the Universal Motion Dancers.\n\n===''Bakit Papa?'' (2003)===\nThe movie was set in Eastside Studios, where the [[SexBomb Girls]] performed some of their dance numbers in the movie. The girl group portrayed secret agents disguised as dancers.\n\n===''Jack Em Popoy: The Puliscredibles'' (2018)===\nOne of the filming locations in the movie ''[[Jack Em Popoy: The Puliscredibles]]'' was in Broadway Centrum, wherein [[Coco Martin]] playing Jacinto Halimuyac represents [[Manila Police District]] in the fictional ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' segment ''Mr. Popu: Poging Pulis''. It is set in Eastside Studios and three of the ''EB!'' hosts, [[Allan K.|Allan K]], [[Pauleen Luna|Pauleen Luna-Sotto]], and [[Luane Dy]] were present in the movie.\n\nThe movie, also an entry to the [[2018 Metro Manila Film Festival|2018 MMFF]], was filmed few months before ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' transferred to APT Studios in December 8, 2018. When the movie was released, ''Eat Bulaga!'' is now broadcast in APT Studios.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Media facilities in the Philippines}}\n{{Eat Bulaga!}}\n\n[[Category:Television studios in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Theaters and concert halls in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Eat Bulaga!]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Quezon City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name                = Broadway Centrum\n| alternate_names     = {{ubl|GMA Broadway Centrum {{nobr|{{small|(1987\u20132012)}}}}|TV5 Broadway Centrum {{nobr|{{small|(2009\u20132013)}}}}|ABS-CBN Broadway Centrum|{{nobr|{{small|(2009-present)}}}}\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|14.611813|121.032245|display=inline}}\n| building_type       = Television studios\n| location            = [[New Manila]], [[Quezon City]]\n| address             = Aurora Boulevard cor. Broadway Avenue, Quezon City\n| owner               = {{ubl|[[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network]] {{small|(1987\u20132012)}}|[[Megaworld Corporation]] {{small|(2012\u20132018)}}}}\n[[Simone Cruz Network Corporation]] {{small|(2030-present)}}}}\n| current_tenants     =  \n| inauguration_date   = 1987\n}}\n\n'''Broadway Centrum''' was a [[television studio]] complex located in the [[New Manila]] district of [[Quezon City]] at Aurora Boulevard cor. Broadway (formerly Do\u00f1a Juana Rodriguez) Avenue, Quezon City. It is currently owned by the Empire East Land Holdings, a subsidiary of [[Megaworld Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Marlon Santeco |url=http://www.empireeastrealproperties.com/promos--updates |title=Empire East Land Holdings, Inc. Megaworld Central Properties, Inc. - Promos & Updates |publisher=Empireeastrealproperties.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref> It was previously owned by [[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network]].\n\nSince its opening, numerous television series have been broadcast live or taped at the facility, including many shows not broadcast on [[GMA Network]]. The complex houses two main studios \u2013 the ''Eastside'' and the ''Westside'' Theaters.\n\nIt is a former studio of the longest-running noontime show in the Philippines, ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'', which lasted for 23 years.\n\n==History==\n\nThe complex was inaugurated to usher [[GMA Network]]'s broadcast in stereovision. In 1987, it served as the live studio of variety shows ''[[Lunch Date]]'', ''[[That's Entertainment (TV program)|That's Entertainment]]'', ''[[Vilma (Philippine TV program)|Vilma!]]'' and ''[[GMA Supershow]]''. In 1995, GMA Network Inc. constructed the second studio within the Broadway Centrum by renovating the Eastside Theater & renamed as \"TAPE Studio, GMA Broadway Studio\" that can accommodate 400 studio audiences for its noontime show ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/599462/Broadway-Centrum-Complex |title=Broadway Centrum - Quezon City |publisher=Wikimapia.org |date= |accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/entertainment/entertainment/view/20100930-295268/Complete-creative-freedom-in-TV5-shows |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306121032/http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/entertainment/entertainment/view/20100930-295268/Complete-creative-freedom-in-TV5-shows |archivedate=2014-03-06 }}</ref>\n\n===Eat Bulaga era===\nThe Eastside Studios of the Broadway Centrum was the main home of the longest-running noontime show when TAPE Inc. constructed this studio and had its first broadcast here on September 16, 1995. From January 1 to March 5, 2010, ''Eat Bulaga!'' temporarily used the Westside Studios while the TAPE Studios was being renovated at that time. ''[[Diz Iz It!]]'' was the last GMA show that used the Westside Studios of Broadway Centrum in 2010. In the same year, the Westside Studios of Broadway Centrum did not have its tenants anymore for GMA Network because some of the network's shows migrated to their very own GMA Network Studios, while TV5 (now [[5 (TV channel)|5]]) leased and revived the Westside Studios with a new and bigger format. The site was owned by GMA Network and also shared with TV5. ''[[The Ryzza Mae Show]]'' was the last GMA show that used the Eastside Studios of the Broadway Centrum in 2013.\n\n===2011\u20132018===\nBoth Studios of the Broadway Centrum were active during that time, the Westside being leased by TV5 and was used for TV shows of the TV5 Entertainment Group such as ''[[Face to Face (talk show)|Face to Face]]'', ''[[The Jose and Wally Show Starring Vic Sotto]]'', ''[[P.O.5]]'', ''Star Factor'', ''[[Hey It's Saberdey!]]'' and ''[[Artista Academy]]'' and others, while the Eastside Studio was used by the longest-running variety show ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' and daily morning talk show ''[[The Ryzza Mae Show]]''.\n\nIn 2012, the Empire East Land Holdings, a subsidiary of [[Megaworld Corporation]] bought the Broadway Centrum to develop a residential condominium and a lifestyle mall at the site of the studio.<ref name=\"megawordunit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/364996/money/companies/megaworld-unit-empire-east-to-spend-p25b-to-buy-more-land-fund-projects |title=Megaworld unit Empire East to spend P25B to buy more land, fund projects &#124; Money &#124; GMA News Online |publisher=Gmanetwork.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"empireeastbroadway\">{{cite web|author=ABS-CBNnews.com |url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/06/10/14/empire-east-develop-broadway-centrum-property |title=Empire East to develop Broadway Centrum property |publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=2016-01-25 |accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"abandonedfactory\">{{cite web |last=Angela |first=Krista |url=http://www.interaksyon.com/business/88767/empire-east-acquiring-abandoned-factory-to-build-new-township-bigger-than-eastwood-city |title=Empire East acquiring abandoned factory to build new township bigger than Eastwood City |publisher=Interaksyon.com |date=2014-06-10 |accessdate=2016-01-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724091910/http://www.interaksyon.com/business/88767/empire-east-acquiring-abandoned-factory-to-build-new-township-bigger-than-eastwood-city# |archive-date=2015-07-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn March 2014, TV5 ended its lease agreement at the Broadway Centrum, particularly at the Westside Studio as an alternate studio of the network as TV5 moved to [[TV5 Media Center]] in Reliance, [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmedia.com.ph/tv5-media-center-groundbreaking-coverage/|title=TV5 Media Center Groundbreaking Coverage|publisher=New Media Philippines|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2013/05/20/944102/kapatid-networks-new-home|title=Kapatid network\u2019s new home|publisher=PhilStar.Com|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://n5e.interaksyon.com/top/4EA1A901A12646E/1001/bagong-tahanan-ng-tv5-sa-mandaluyong-silipin |title=Bagong Tahanan ng TV5 sa Mandaluyong, Silipin |publisher=News5 Everywhere |accessdate=21 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224111513/http://n5e.interaksyon.com/top/4EA1A901A12646E/1001/bagong-tahanan-ng-tv5-sa-mandaluyong-silipin |archivedate=24 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe Broadway Centrum became a landmark once again thanks to the popularity of the [[AlDub]] loveteam in Eat Bulaga's segment, ''[[Kalyeserye]]'' where some memorable moments were set at the Broadway.\n\n===Demise and fate===\nOn December 7, 2018, the Broadway Centrum finally ended its long 31-year run as ''Eat Bulaga!'' broadcast its last episode there and, since December 8, 2018, has moved to their new state-of-the-art studio, the [[APT Studios]], located in [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], thus ending their 23-year tenure at the old studio.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anarcon |first1=James Patrick |title=Eat Bulaga looks back on RPN-9, ABS-CBN days as it transfers to new studio |url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/28916/eat-bulaga-looks-back-on-rpn-9-abs-cbn-days-as-it-transfers-to-new-studio |website=PEP.ph |accessdate=6 January 2019 |date=8 December 2018}}</ref> It is set to be demolished and redeveloped into a high-rise condominium and a mall complex which will be built by Empire East Land Holdings, the 1.7 hectare property's new owners.And Will Be Owned By Simone Cruz Network Corp In 2030 <ref name=\"megawordunit\" /><ref name=\"empireeastbroadway\" /><ref name=\"abandonedfactory\" />\n''\n\n==Shows produced at Broadway Centrum==\nBelow is a partial list of programs that have taped episodes at the studios.\n{{Div col}}\n*''[[Artista Academy]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Beh Bote Nga]]'' (1999\u20132000)\n*''Bitoys Adventures In Bilibkaba'' (1998\u20132000)\n*''[[Born to Be a Star (TV series)|Born to Be a Star]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Bubble Gang]]'' (1995\u20132000)\n*''D.A.T.S.'' (1997\u20131999)\n*''[[Digital LG Quiz]]'' (1999\u20132004)\n*''[[Diz Iz It!]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' (1995\u20132018)\n*''[[Face to Face (talk show)|Face to Face]]'' (2010\u20132013)\n*''[[GMA Supershow]]'' (1987\u20131997)\n*''[[GoBingo]]'' (1996\u20131999)\n*''Guwapings Live!'' (1992)\n*''[[HAPPinas Happy Hour]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Happy Truck HAPPinas]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Hey It's Saberdey!]]'' (2011\u20132012)\n*''[[It's Showtime (variety show)|It's Showtime]]'' (2012-present)\n*''Jamming'' (1999-2000)\n*''[[Katok Mga Misis!]]'' (1995\u20131997)\n*''Killer Karaoke: Pinoy Naman'' (2013\u20132014)\n*''[[Lunch Date]]'' (1987\u20131993)\n*''[[Martin After Dark]]'' (1988\u20131993)\n*''[[Move It: Clash of the Streetdancers|Move It!]]'' (2015)\n*''Mixed N.U.T.S.: Numerong Unong Terrific Show'' (1994\u20131997)\n*''Oooops With Wendell & Antonio'' (1997\u20131998)\n*''[[P.O.5]]'' (2010\u20132011)\n*''[[Rising Stars Philippines]]'' (2015)\n*''[[SST: Salo-Salo Together|Salo-Salo Together (SST)]]'' (1993\u20131995)\n''[[It's Showtime]]'' (2012-present)\n*''[[SOP (TV program)|SOP]]'' (1997\u20132000)\n*''Shades'' (1987\u20131988)\n*''[[Showbiz Central]]'' (2007\u20132012)\n*''Show & Tell'' (1994\u20131995)\n*''[[StarStruck (Filipino TV series)|StarStruck]]'' (2003\u20132007, 2009\u20132010)\n*''Star Factor'' (2010)\n*''[[Sunday Funday (TV program)|Sunday Funday]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Talentadong Pinoy]]'' (2008\u20132013, 2014)\n*''Tanghalan ng Kampeon'' (1989\u20131994)\n*''[[That's Entertainment (TV series)|That's Entertainment]]'' (1987\u20131996)\n*''[[The 700 Club|The 700 Club Asia]]'' (1995\u20132000)\n*''[[The Jose and Wally Show Starring Vic Sotto]]'' (2011\u20132012)\n*''[[The Ryzza Mae Show]]'' (2013\u20132015)\n*''[[Tok! Tok! Tok! Isang Milyon Pasok!]]'' (2007\u20132009)\n*''[[S-Files]]'' (1998\u20132007)\n*''[[Vilma!]]'' (1987\u20131995)\n*''[[Walang Tulugan with the Master Showman]]'' (1997\u20132010)\n*''What Went Wrong'' (1996\u20131999)\n*''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (Philippine game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' (2009\u20132015)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nBroadway Centrum, for the following movies, was usually used for taping or shooting:  \n\n===''Sige Ihataw Mo'' (1993)===\nThe movie is set in Westside Studios, where some of the pivotal scenes were shot.  It is also headlined by the Universal Motion Dancers.\n\n===''Bakit Papa?'' (2003)===\nThe movie was set in Eastside Studios, where the [[SexBomb Girls]] performed some of their dance numbers in the movie. The girl group portrayed secret agents disguised as dancers.\n\n===''Jack Em Popoy: The Puliscredibles'' (2018)===\nOne of the filming locations in the movie ''[[Jack Em Popoy: The Puliscredibles]]'' was in Broadway Centrum, wherein [[Coco Martin]] playing Jacinto Halimuyac represents [[Manila Police District]] in the fictional ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' segment ''Mr. Popu: Poging Pulis''. It is set in Eastside Studios and three of the ''EB!'' hosts, [[Allan K.|Allan K]], [[Pauleen Luna|Pauleen Luna-Sotto]], and [[Luane Dy]] were present in the movie.\n\nThe movie, also an entry to the [[2018 Metro Manila Film Festival|2018 MMFF]], was filmed few months before ''[[Eat Bulaga!]]'' transferred to APT Studios in December 8, 2018. When the movie was released, ''Eat Bulaga!'' is now broadcast in APT Studios.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Media facilities in the Philippines}}\n{{Eat Bulaga!}}\n\n[[Category:Television studios in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Theaters and concert halls in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Eat Bulaga!]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Quezon City]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toIt's Showtime(link changed toIt's Showtime (variety show)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broadway_Centrum"}
{"title_page": "Kharkiv National University of Radioelectronics", "text_new": "{{Infobox University  \n|name               = Kharkiv National University of Radio Electronics\n|former_name        = Kharkiv Engineering-Building Institute (1930-1966)<br>Kharkiv Institute of Radio Electronics (1966-1993)<br>Kharkiv Technical University of Radioelectronics (1993-2001)\n|other_name         = NURE\n|image              = KharkovRadioInstituteWinter.jpg\n|image_size         = 250px\n|established        = 8/11/1930\n|students           = 8000+\n|rector             = [[Valerii Semenets]]\n| city              = [[Kharkiv|Kharkiv (\u043c.\u0425\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0456\u0432)]] \n| country           = [[Ukraine|Ukraine (\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0430)]]\n| website           = {{URL|www.nure.ua}}\n|address            = \u043f\u0440-\u0442 \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0438, 14 (14 Nauky Avenue)\n}}\n\n'''Kharkiv National University of Radio Electronics (NURE)''' is a higher education institution of the highest level of accreditation in [[Ukraine]]. It is one of the oldest technology universities in Ukraine, with over 7000 students and 30 scientific centers.\n\nIt has strong research and education capabilities in electrical engineering, electronics, telecommunications, ICT and computer technologies.\n\nNURE hosts the International Academy of Applied Radio & Electronics. NURE pioneered the development of distance education in Ukraine. It has a high expertise in introduction of innovative technologies into education and business.\n\n\n\n==History of NURE==\n[[File:Nure-brand-book-1-1024 cr2.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Logo NURE]]\n[[File:EmblemaHGI.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Emblem of the Kharkov Geodetic Institute]]\nThe history of NURE begins in 1930 when Kharkiv Engineering-Building Institute (KEBI) was founded on the basis of building faculty of [[National Technical University \"Kharkiv Polytechnical Institute\"|Kharkiv Polytechnical Institute]] and architectural faculty of Kharkiv Art Institute. In 1934 Kharkiv Geodetic Institute and Scientific Research Institute of Geodesy and Cartography entered the structure of the institute. In 10 years KEBI became the largest higher education institution of Ukraine numbering 1734 students, 200 teachers and 4 faculties: Architectural, Building, Sanitary and Geodetic.\n\nIn 1966 KIMBAC was given a name of Kharkiv Institute of Radio Electronics (KIRE)\nSoon after the declaration of independence of Ukraine KIRE got the status of University and became Kharkiv Technical University of Radio Electronics (KTURE) in 1993.\n\nIn 2001 the status of the University was advanced to the National University.\n\n==University structure==\nNURE consists of 8 faculties and 34 departments:\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-computer-science Faculty of Computer Sciences (CS)]\n** Artificial Intelligence (AI)  \n** Information Control Systems (ICS)                \n** Systems Engineering (SE)\n** Computer Software (CSoft)\n** Engineering and Computer \u0421raphics (ECG)\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-computer-engineering-and-control Faculty of Computer Engineering and Control (CEC)]\n** Electronic Computers (EC)\n** \u0421omputer intelligent technologies and systems (CITS)\n** Computer Aided Design of Computers (CDA)\n** Information Technologies Security (ITS)\n** Philosophy\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-information-and-analytical-technologies-and-managment Faculty of Information and Analytical Technologies and Management (ITM)]\n** Applied Mathematics\n** Informatics\n** Economic \u0421ybernetics and Management of Economic Security\n** Higher Mathematics\n** Social Informatics\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-information-radio-technologies-and-technical-information-security Faculty of Information Radio Technologies and Technical Information Security (IRTIS)]\n** Computer Radio Engineering and Technical Information Security Systems (CRETISS)\n** Radiotechnologies Information and Communication Systems (RICS)\n** Media Engineering and Information Radio Electronic Systems (MEIRES)\n** Microprocessor Technologies and Systems (MTS)\n** Foreign Languages\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-infocommunications \u0406nfocommunications (IC)]\n** \u0406nfocommunication Engineering (ICE)\n** Information and Network Engineering (INE)\n** Metrology and Technical Expertise (MTE)\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-automa-tion-and-computer-technologies Faculty of Automation and Computer Technologies (ACT)]\n** Design and Operation of Electronic Devices (DOED)\n** Computer-Integrated Technologies, Automation and Mechatronics (CITAM)\n** Physics\n** Occupational Safety\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-electronic-and-biomedical-engineering Faculty of Electronic and Biomedical Engineering (ELBE)]\n** Microelectronics, Electronic Devices and Appliances (MEDA)\n** Physical Foundations of Electronic Engineering (PFEE)\n** Biomedical Engineering (BME)\n** Physical Training and Sports (PTS)\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-foreign-citizens-training Faculty of Foreign Citizens Training]\n** Language Training\n** Natural Sciences\n** History, language and culture of Ukraine\n\n==Awards and reputation==\nThe University ranks first among technical universities of Ukraine by the results of the rankings made by the Ministry of Education and Science, Youth and Sport of Ukraine (according to \u201cEducation of Ukraine\u201d \u211626 (1295) of 25 June 2012 and the website http://euroosvita.net ).\n\n13th place among the Ukraine institutions according to Scimago IR in 2018[https://www.scimagoir.com/rankings.php?country=UKR].\n\nIn the QS \u0415merging Europe and central Asia University Rankings 2020 NURE was ranked 241-250 [https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/eeca-rankings/2020].\n \nIn January 2020 the University ranked 9th in the Ranking Web of Universities[http://www.webometrics.info/en/Europe/Ukraine%20].\n\nIn the [http://www.euroosvita.net/index.php/?category=1&id=5209 Top-200] NURE ranked 23 among higher educational institutions of Ukraine.\n\nIn uniRank 2020 University Ranking NURE placed 38th of 171 recognized Ukrainian higher-education institutions[https://www.4icu.org/ua/].\n\nIn Nature Index in 2018 NURE ranked 8th among 13 Ukrainian universities[https://www.natureindex.com/annual-tables/2018/institution/academic/all/countries-Ukraine].\n\n==International==\nStrong cooperation within [[TEMPUS]], [[Horizon 2020]], INTAS, INCO-Copernicus, EU Joint- and Double-Degree Master programs, etc. allowed NURE to become one of the first HEIs in Ukraine which introduced the Bologna principles and ECTS to its practices.\nUniversity aims to integration of  in the international, particularly European scientific and educational space, to the creation of the operational development of the information and communications field as a modern mechanism of international activities.\nNURE widely develop international contacts through cooperation with universities in other countries and foreign companies. A large number of faculty, staff, graduate students go abroad to participate in academic conferences, research and internships, as well as accept foreign specialists at university. Almost all of the departments have memorandums and agreements on cooperation with foreign companies.\n\n===International partners===\n* [[University of Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]] (JyU), [[Finland]]\n* [[Linnaeus University]], [[Sweden]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nure.ua/en/ Official site] {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://lib.nure.ua/ru Library] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://cist.nure.ua/ Timetable] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [https://dl.nure.ua/?lang=en Distance Learning] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{Higher education in Kharkiv Oblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord|50|00|54|N|36|13|40|E|type:landmark_source:kolossus-ruwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kharkiv]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kharkiv]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1962]]\n[[Category:National universities in Ukraine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox University  \n|name               = Kharkiv National University of Radio Electronics\n|former_name        = Kharkiv Engineering-Building Institute (1930-1966)<br>Kharkiv Institute of Radio Electronics (1966-1993)<br>Kharkiv Technical University of Radioelectronics (1993-2001)\n|other_name         = NURE\n|image              = KharkovRadioInstituteWinter.jpg\n|image_size         = 250px\n|established        = 8/11/1930\n|students           = 8000+\n|rector             = [[Valerii Semenets]]\n| city              = [[Kharkiv|Kharkiv (\u043c.\u0425\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0456\u0432)]] \n| country           = [[Ukraine|Ukraine (\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0430)]]\n| website           = {{URL|www.nure.ua}}\n|address            = \u043f\u0440-\u0442 \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0438, 14 (14 Nauky Avenue)\n}}\n\n'''Kharkiv National University of Radio Electronics (NURE)''' is a higher education institution of the highest level of accreditation in [[Ukraine]]. It is one of the oldest technology universities in Ukraine, with over 7000 students and 30 scientific centers.\n\nIt has strong research and education capabilities in electrical engineering, electronics, telecommunications, ICT and computer technologies.\n\nNURE hosts the International Academy of Applied Radio & Electronics. NURE pioneered the development of distance education in Ukraine. It has a high expertise in introduction of innovative technologies into education and business.\n\n\n\n==History of NURE==\n[[File:Nure-brand-book-1-1024 cr2.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Logo NURE]]\n[[File:EmblemaHGI.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Emblem of the Kharkov Geodetic Institute]]\nThe history of NURE begins in 1930 when Kharkiv Engineering-Building Institute (KEBI) was founded on the basis of building faculty of [[National Technical University \"Kharkiv Polytechnical Institute\"|Kharkiv Polytechnical Institute]] and architectural faculty of Kharkiv Art Institute. In 1934 Kharkiv Geodetic Institute and Scientific Research Institute of Geodesy and Cartography entered the structure of the institute. In 10 years KEBI became the largest higher education institution of Ukraine numbering 1734 students, 200 teachers and 4 faculties: Architectural, Building, Sanitary and Geodetic.\n\nIn 1966 KIMBAC was given a name of Kharkiv Institute of Radio Electronics (KIRE)\nSoon after the declaration of independence of Ukraine KIRE got the status of University and became Kharkiv Technical University of Radio Electronics (KTURE) in 1993.\n\nIn 2001 the status of the University was advanced to the National University.\n\n==University structure==\nNURE consists of 8 faculties and 34 departments:\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-computer-science Faculty of Computer Sciences (CS)]\n** Artificial Intelligence (AI)  \n** Information Control Systems (ICS)                \n** Systems Engineering (SE)\n** Computer Software (CSoft)\n** Engineering and Computer \u0421raphics (ECG)\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-computer-engineering-and-control Faculty of Computer Engineering and Control (CEC)]\n** Electronic Computers (EC)\n** \u0421omputer intelligent technologies and systems (CITS)\n** Computer Aided Design of Computers (CDA)\n** Information Technologies Security (ITS)\n** Philosophy\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-information-and-analytical-technologies-and-managment Faculty of Information and Analytical Technologies and Management (ITM)]\n** Applied Mathematics\n** Informatics\n** Economic \u0421ybernetics and Management of Economic Security\n** Higher Mathematics\n** Social Informatics\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-information-radio-technologies-and-technical-information-security Faculty of Information Radio Technologies and Technical Information Security (IRTIS)]\n** Computer Radio Engineering and Technical Information Security Systems (CRETISS)\n** Radiotechnologies Information and Communication Systems (RICS)\n** Media Engineering and Information Radio Electronic Systems (MEIRES)\n** Microprocessor Technologies and Systems (MTS)\n** Foreign Languages\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-infocommunications \u0406nfocommunications (IC)]\n** \u0406nfocommunication Engineering (ICE)\n** Information and Network Engineering (INE)\n** Metrology and Technical Expertise (MTE)\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-automa-tion-and-computer-technologies Faculty of Automation and Computer Technologies (ACT)]\n** Design and Operation of Electronic Devices (DOED)\n** Computer-Integrated Technologies, Automation and Mechatronics (CITAM)\n** Physics\n** Occupational Safety\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-electronic-and-biomedical-engineering Faculty of Electronic and Biomedical Engineering (ELBE)]\n** Microelectronics, Electronic Devices and Appliances (MEDA)\n** Physical Foundations of Electronic Engineering (PFEE)\n** Biomedical Engineering (BME)\n** Physical Training and Sports (PTS)\n* [http://nure.ua/en/faculty/faculty-of-foreign-citizens-training Faculty of Foreign Citizens Training]\n** Language Training\n** Natural Sciences\n** History, language and culture of Ukraine\n\n==Awards and reputation==\nThe University ranks first among technical universities of Ukraine by the results of the rankings made by the Ministry of Education and Science, Youth and Sport of Ukraine (according to \u201cEducation of Ukraine\u201d \u211626 (1295) of 25 June 2012 and the website http://euroosvita.net ).\n\n13th place among the Ukraine institutions according to Scimago IR in 2018[https://www.scimagoir.com/rankings.php?country=UKR].\n \nIn January 2019 the University ranked 16th in the Ranking Web of Universities[http://www.webometrics.info/en/Europe/Ukraine%20].\n\nIn the [http://www.euroosvita.net/index.php/?category=1&id=5209 Top-200] NURE ranked 23 among higher educational institutions of Ukraine.\n\nIn u