s in Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "\u0413\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0454\u043b\u044f\u043d\u0456\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards and reputation:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kharkiv_National_University_of_Radioelectronics"}
{"title_page": "Briggs' Plan", "text_new": "[[File:New Village in Malaya, 1950s.jpg|thumb|alt=|Photograph of a model New Village internment camp, designed as part of the Briggs' Plan to segregate the largely ethnic [[Malaysian Chinese]] rural workers from communist guerrillas. ]]\nThe '''Briggs' Plan''' was a military plan devised by [[United Kingdom|British]] General Sir [[Harold Rawdon Briggs|Harold Briggs]] shortly after his appointment in 1950 as Director of Operations during the [[Malayan Emergency]] (1948-1960). The plan aimed to defeat the Malayan [[communist]] guerrillas by cutting them off from their sources of support amongst the rural population.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Massacre in Malaya: Exposing Britain's My Lai|last=Hale|first=Christopher|publisher=The History Press|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7524-8701-4|location=Brimscombe Port|pages=326}}</ref> To achieve this a large programme of [[forced resettlement]] of Malayan peasantry was undertaken, under which about 500,000 people (roughly ten percent of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya's]] population) were forcefully removed from their land and imprisoned in internment camps called \"[[New Villages]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=British  Counterinsurgency|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-0-230-29824-8|location=Basingstoke|pages=48}}</ref> During the Emergency there were over 400 of these guarded camps. Furthermore, 10,000 [[Malaysian Chinese]] people suspected of being communist sympathisers were deported to mainland China by 1949 where many were then executed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Blood Never Dried: A People's History of the British Empire|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Bookmarks Publications|year=2013|isbn=978-1-909026-29-2|location=London|pages=218}}</ref> The Malayan aboriginals, the [[Orang Asli]], were also targeted for forced relocation by the Briggs' Plan because the British believing that they were supporting the communists.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Violence and the Dream People: The Orang Asli in the Emergency 1948-1960|last=D. Leary|first=John|publisher=Ohio University Press|year=1995|isbn=0-89680-186-1|location=Athens|pages=42-43}}</ref>\n\nMany of the practices necessary for the Briggs' Plan were prohibited by the [[Geneva Conventions]] and [[customary international law]] which stated that the destruction of property must not happen unless rendered absolutely necessary by military operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.csbsju.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://en.wikipedia.org/&httpsredir=1&article=1014&context=polsci_pubs|title=The Other Forgotten War: Understanding Atrocities during the Malayan Emergency Malayan Emergency|last=Siver|first=Christi|date=2009|url-status=live|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBritish authority in Malaya's rural areas had only been tenuously reestablished following the withdrawal of [[Japan]] at the end of [[World War II]]. The British regarded a group of about 500,000 \"[[squatter]]s\", largely of [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] descent, who practiced [[small-scale agriculture]], generally lacked legal title to their land, and were largely outside the reach of the colonial administration, as particularly problematic. Many of these Chinese people had been forced to live in isolated communities to avoid slaughter by the occupying Japanese.\n\nIn order to force rural workers off their land, the British military burned down rural villages, destroyed crops and killed livestock. Some villagers would later receive compensation but most would not.<ref>{{Cite book|title=British Counterinsurgency|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-0-230-29824-8|location=Basingstoke|pages=52}}</ref> These communities formed the backbone of the [[Malayan Communist Party]] (MCP), their armed wing the [[Malayan National Liberation Army]] (MNLA), and their civilian supplies and intelligence network the 'Min Yuen'.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many rural workers were sympathetic to [[communism]] due to their role of the MCP as leaders of the WWII [[Anti-Japanese resistance]] movement. Other factors which led to support for the communists include; the desire for Malayan independence from Britain, the communist victory in China, the communist role in leading the Malayan trade union movement, economic inequality and poverty post-WWII and resentment towards the racism of British rule. Other rural workers who did not want to support the communist guerrillas did so anyway due to fear of backlash by their neighbours and the communist guerrillas.\n\nBy isolating this population in the \"new villages\", the British were able to stem the critical flow of food, information, and recruits from peasants to guerillas.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Alias Chin Peng: My Side of History|last=Peng|first=Chin|publisher=Media Masters|year=2003|isbn=981-04-8693-6|location=Singapore|pages=268}}</ref> The new settlements were guarded around-the-clock by police and many were partially fortified with barbed wire and sentry towers. This served the twofold purpose of preventing those who were so inclined from getting out and voluntarily aiding the guerrilla, and of preventing the guerrilla from getting in and extracting help via persuasion or intimidation. 450 new settlements were created in this process and it is estimated that 470,509 people, 400,000 of them Chinese, were involved in the program. The [[Malaysian Chinese Association]], (known then as the Malayan Chinese Association), played a crucial role in implementing the programme.<ref name=\"Gin2009\">{{cite book|author=Ooi Keat Gin|title=Historical Dictionary of Malaysia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=assDznc7EN4C|accessdate=16 February 2013|date=11 May 2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6305-7|pages=lvii, 185}}</ref>\n\nThe British also tried to win the support of some of the internees by providing them with education and health services. Some New Villages were equipped with amenities such as electricity and piped water and surrounded with perimeter fencing and armed guards to keep the civilians from escaping\u2013 many of whom had formerly been in the MCP or had been forced to provide assistance. It was hoped that by providing the largely ethnic Chinese communities with such facilities, they would be converted from \"reservoirs of resentment into bastions of loyal Malayan citizenry\". However, critics argue that the homogenous nature of New Villages &mdash; with the few multiracial ones eventually failing or turning into [[ghetto]]es &mdash; worked against this goal, instead accentuating communalist fervour and causing [[racial polarisation]], especially in politics, as electoral constituencies would now be delineated more along racial lines.\n\nPreviously, the Chinese rural workers and peasants had been spread out geographically, but the Briggs' Plan would now bring together rural Chinese from all over the country and concentrate them in the New Villages. There was significant resentment towards the programme both among the Chinese and Malays. The Chinese frequently suffered from [[collective punishment]], [[preventive detention]] and [[summary deportation]] aimed at weeding out communist supporters, while the Malays were incensed at the infrastructure provided for the New Villages as their own settlements remained undeveloped.<ref>Ongkili, pp. 85&ndash;88.</ref> One example of this collective punishment comes from [[Tanjung Malim]] where the British put the civilian population on rice rations in order to stop them from supporting the communist guerrillas. When this did not work, [[Gerald Templer]] halfed the rice rations for civilians within the area and imposed a 22 hour curfew.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Small Wars Faraway Places: Global Insurrection and the Making of the Modern World 1945-1965|last=Michael|first=Burleigh|publisher=Viking - Penguin Group|year=2013|isbn=978-0-670-02545-9|location=New York|pages=178}}</ref>\n\n== Similar examples ==\nForcibly removing a population that might be sympathetic to guerrillas was a [[counter-insurgency]] (COIN) technique which the British had used before, [[Second Boer War#Concentration camps .281900.E2.80.931902.29|notably initiated]] by [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]] against the [[Boer Commando]]s in the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902). \n\nThe Briggs' Plan and the New Village system became a model for British counterinsurgency efforts in Kenya during the [[Mau Mau Uprising]].\n\nUpon completion of the programme, the British initiated the [[Hunger Drive]] in an effort to flush out the communists from the jungle.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[New Village]] / Chinese New Village\n*[[Malayan Emergency]]\n*[[Malayan Communist Party]]\n*[[Internment]]\n*[[Malayan National Liberation Army]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \n\n{{Communism in Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Forced migration]]\n[[Category:Internments]]\n[[Category:Malayan Emergency]]\n[[Category:Internment camps]]\n[[Category:British war crimes]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:New Village in Malaya, 1950s.jpg|thumb|alt=|Photograph of a model New Village internment camp, designed as part of the Briggs' Plan to segregate the largely ethnic [[Malaysian Chinese]] rural workers from communist guerrillas. ]]\nThe '''Briggs' Plan''' was a military plan devised by [[United Kingdom|British]] General Sir [[Harold Rawdon Briggs|Harold Briggs]] shortly after his appointment in 1950 as Director of Operations during the [[Malayan Emergency]] (1948-1960). The plan aimed to defeat the Malayan [[communist]] guerrillas by cutting them off from their sources of support amongst the rural population.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Massacre in Malaya: Exposing Britain's My Lai|last=Hale|first=Christopher|publisher=The History Press|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7524-8701-4|location=Brimscombe Port|pages=326}}</ref> To achieve this a large programme of [[forced resettlement]] of Malayan peasantry was undertaken, under which about 500,000 people (roughly ten percent of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya's]] population) were forcefully removed from their land and imprisoned in internment camps called \"[[New Villages]]\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=British  Counterinsurgency|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-0-230-29824-8|location=Basingstoke|pages=48}}</ref> During the Emergency there were over 400 of these guarded camps. Furthermore, 10,000 [[Malaysian Chinese]] people suspected of being communist sympathisers were deported to mainland China by 1949 where many were then executed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Blood Never Dried: A People's History of the British Empire|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Bookmarks Publications|year=2013|isbn=978-1-909026-29-2|location=London|pages=218}}</ref> The Malayan aboriginals, the [[Orang Asli]], were also targetted for forced relocation by the Briggs Plan because the British believing that they were supporting the communists.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Violence and the Dream People: The Orang Asli in the Emergency 1948-1960|last=D. Leary|first=John|publisher=Ohio University Press|year=1995|isbn=0-89680-186-1|location=Athens|pages=42-43}}</ref>\n\nMany of the practices necessary for the Briggs' Plan were prohibited by the [[Geneva Conventions]] and [[customary international law]] which stated that the destruction of property must not happen unless rendered absolutely necessary by military operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.csbsju.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://en.wikipedia.org/&httpsredir=1&article=1014&context=polsci_pubs|title=The Other Forgotten War: Understanding Atrocities during the Malayan Emergency Malayan Emergency|last=Siver|first=Christi|date=2009|url-status=live|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBritish authority in Malaya's rural areas had only been tenuously reestablished following the withdrawal of [[Japan]] at the end of [[World War II]]. The British regarded a group of about 500,000 \"[[squatter]]s\", largely of [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] descent, who practiced [[small-scale agriculture]], generally lacked legal title to their land, and were largely outside the reach of the colonial administration, as particularly problematic. Many of these Chinese people had been forced to live in isolated communities to avoid slaughter by the occupying Japanese.\n\nIn order to force rural workers off their land, the British military burned down rural villages, destroyed crops and killed livestock. Some villagers would later receive compensation but most would not.<ref>{{Cite book|title=British Counterinsurgency|last=Newsinger|first=John|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2015|isbn=978-0-230-29824-8|location=Basingstoke|pages=52}}</ref> These communities formed the backbone of the [[Malayan Communist Party]] (MCP), their armed wing the [[Malayan National Liberation Army]] (MNLA), and their civilian supplies and inteligence network the 'Min Yuen'.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many rural workers were sympathetic to [[communism]] due to their role of the MCP as leaders of the WWII [[Anti-Japanese resistance]] movement. Other factors which led to support for the communists include; the desire for Malayan independence from Britain, the communist victory in China, the communist role in leading the Malayan trade union movement, economic inequality and poverty post-WWII and resentment towards the racism of British rule. Other rural workers who did not want to support the communist guerrillas did so anyway due to fear of backlash by their neighbours and the communist guerrillas.\n\nBy isolating this population in the \"new villages\", the British were able to stem the critical flow of food, information, and recruits from peasants to guerillas.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Alias Chin Peng: My Side of History|last=Peng|first=Chin|publisher=Media Masters|year=2003|isbn=981-04-8693-6|location=Singapore|pages=268}}</ref> The new settlements were guarded around-the-clock by police and many were partially fortified with barbed wire and sentry towers. This served the twofold purpose of preventing those who were so inclined from getting out and voluntarily aiding the guerrilla, and of preventing the guerrilla from getting in and extracting help via persuasion or intimidation. 450 new settlements were created in this process and it is estimated that 470,509 people, 400,000 of them Chinese, were involved in the program. The [[Malaysian Chinese Association]], (known then as the Malayan Chinese Association), played a crucial role in implementing the programme.<ref name=\"Gin2009\">{{cite book|author=Ooi Keat Gin|title=Historical Dictionary of Malaysia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=assDznc7EN4C|accessdate=16 February 2013|date=11 May 2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6305-7|pages=lvii, 185}}</ref>\n\nThe British also tried to win the support of some of the internees by providing them with education and health services. Some New Villages were equipped with amenities such as electricity and piped water and surrounded with perimeter fencing and armed guards to keep the civilians from escaping\u2013 many of whom had formerly been in the MCP or had been forced to provide assistance. It was hoped that by providing the largely ethnic Chinese communities with such facilities, they would be converted from \"reservoirs of resentment into bastions of loyal Malayan citizenry\". However, critics argue that the homogenous nature of New Villages &mdash; with the few multiracial ones eventually failing or turning into [[ghetto]]es &mdash; worked against this goal, instead accentuating communalist fervour and causing [[racial polarisation]], especially in politics, as electoral constituencies would now be delineated more along racial lines.\n\nPreviously, the Chinese rural workers and peasants had been spread out geographically, but the Briggs Plan would now bring together rural Chinese from all over the country and concentrate them in the New Villages. There was significant resentment towards the programme both among the Chinese and Malays. The Chinese frequently suffered from [[collective punishment]], [[preventive detention]] and [[summary deportation]] aimed at weeding out communist supporters, while the Malays were incensed at the infrastructure provided for the New Villages as their own settlements remained undeveloped.<ref>Ongkili, pp. 85&ndash;88.</ref> One example of this collective punishment comes from [[Tanjung Malim]] where the British put the civilian population on rice rations in order to stop them from supporting the communist guerrillas. When this did not work, [[Gerald Templer]] halfed the rice rations for civilians within the area and imposed a 22 hour curfew.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Small Wars Faraway Places: Global Insurrection and the Making of the Modern World 1945-1965|last=Michael|first=Burleigh|publisher=Viking - Penguin Group|year=2013|isbn=978-0-670-02545-9|location=New York|pages=178}}</ref>\n\n== Similar examples ==\nForcibly removing a population that might be sympathetic to guerrillas was a [[counter-insurgency]] (COIN) technique which the British had used before, [[Second Boer War#Concentration camps .281900.E2.80.931902.29|notably initiated]] by [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]] against the [[Boer Commando]]s in the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902). \n\nThe Briggs' Plan and the New Village system became a model for British counterinsurgency efforts in Kenya during the [[Mau Mau Uprising]].\n\nUpon completion of the programme, the British initiated the [[Hunger Drive]] in an effort to flush out the communists from the jungle.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[New Village]] / Chinese New Village\n*[[Malayan Emergency]]\n*[[Malayan Communist Party]]\n*[[Internment]]\n*[[Malayan National Liberation Army]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \n\n{{Communism in Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Forced migration]]\n[[Category:Internments]]\n[[Category:Malayan Emergency]]\n[[Category:Internment camps]]\n[[Category:British war crimes]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Briggs%27_Plan"}
{"title_page": "Kentucky Route 34", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=KY\n|type=KY\n|route=34\n|maint=[[Kentucky Transportation Cabinet|KYTC]]\n|alternate_name=\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=240|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Kentucky Route 34}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=KY 34 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=21.828\n|length_round=3\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"ktc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planning.kytc.ky.gov/data_reports.asp |title=Kentucky Transportation Cabinet - Division of Planning |accessdate=2008-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070430064216/http://www.planning.kytc.ky.gov/data_reports.asp |archivedate=2007-04-30 }}</ref>\n|established=\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=KY|US|68|KY|52}} near [[Mitchellsburg, Kentucky|Mitchellsburg]]\n|junction=\n{{Jct|state=KY|KY|300}} in [[Parksville, Kentucky|Parksville]]<br>\n{{Jct|state=KY|US-Byp|127|US-Byp|150}} west of [[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]]<br>\n{{Jct|state=KY|US|150|KY|52}} in Danville<br>\n{{Jct|state=KY|US|127}} in Danville<br>\n{{Jct|state=KY|US|27}} east of Danville\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b=Lexington Road east of [[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]]\n|counties=[[Boyle County, Kentucky|Boyle]], [[Garrard County, Kentucky|Garrard]]\n|previous_type=KY\n|previous_route=33\n|next_type=KY\n|next_route=35\n}}\n'''Kentucky Route 34''' ('''KY 34''') is a {{convert|21.828|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}}, east&ndash;west, 2-lane, [[state highway]] in [[Kentucky]] managed by the [[Kentucky Transportation Cabinet]].\n\nKY 34 begins at [[US 68]] and [[KY 52]] near [[Mitchellsburg, Kentucky|Mitchellsburg]] and goes through [[Boyle County, Kentucky|Boyle]] and [[Garrard County, Kentucky|Garrard]] counties before terminating at Lexington Road (Old US 27) east of [[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]] just beyond [[US 27]]. KY 34 formerly terminated at US 27 before US 27 was rebuilt to the west.  It serves as a primary connector between Danville and [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]].\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|state=KY|length_ref=<ref name=\"ktc\"/>}}\n{{KYint\n|county=Boyle\n|cspan=16\n|location=none\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|68|name1=[[KY 52]]<!--not signed here-->}}\n}}\n{{KYint\n|location=Brumfield\n|mile=1.223\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1894|dir1=north|name1=Brumfield Road}}\n|notes=former US 68 east\n}}\n{{KYint\n|location=Mitchellsburg\n|lspan=2\n|mile=3.024\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1856|name1=Scrubgrass Road}}\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=3.273\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1108|dir1=south|name1=Mitchellsburg Knob Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of KY 1108\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|location=Parksville\n|lspan=2\n|mile=6.115\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1822|dir1=south|name1=Johnson Branch Road|road=Harberson Lane}}\n|notes=West end of KY 1822 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=6.298\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|300|dir1=east|name1=Alum Springs Road<!--is this a current street name?-->}}\n|notes=Western terminus of KY 300\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|location=none\n|mile=7.207\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1822|dir1=north|name1=Parksville Cross Pike<!--is this a current street name?-->}}\n|notes=east end of KY 1822 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|location=Danville\n|lspan=9\n|mile=12.262\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US-Byp|127|dab1=Danville|US-Byp|150|dab2=Danville}}\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=13.629\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|150|dir1=west|KY|52|dir2=west|name2=Perryville Road}}\n|notes=West end of US 150 / KY 52 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=13.893\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|127|dir1=north|name1=Maple Avenue}}\n|notes=West end of US 127 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|127|dir1=south|name1=South 4th Street}}\n|notes=east end of US 127 south overlap (eastbound)\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=14.469\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|33|dir1=north|name1=North 3rd Street}}\n|notes=East end of US 127 north overlap (westbound)\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=14.801\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|150|dir1=east|KY|52|dir2=east|name2=Stanford Avenue}}\n|notes=East end of US 150 / KY 52 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=15.063\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|2324|dir1=west|name1=East Lexington Avenue}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of KY 2324\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=16.541\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1805|dir1=south|name1=Goggin Lane}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of KY 1805\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=16.703\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|2168|dir1=west}}<!--anything signed here?-->\n|notes=Eastern terminus of KY 2168\n}}\n{{KYint\n|county=Garrard\n|cspan=2\n|location=none\n|mile=21.705\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|27|city1=Lexington|city2=Lancaster}}\n}}\n{{KYint\n|location=none\n|mile=21.828\n|road=Camp Dick Road\n|notes=former US 27\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n\n==Alternate names==\nKY 34 has other names along its path:\n*'''Lebanon Road''' from its western terminus into Danville.\n*'''Main Street''' ([[US 150]] and [[US 127]]) in Danville\n*'''Wilderness Road''' in Danville\n*'''Lexington Road''' from Danville to the Garrard County line\n*'''Chenault Bridge Road''' in Garrard County\n\n==Future==\n{{update|date=November 2014}}\nA new route (KY 2168) is planned to connect KY 34 and KY 33 northeast of Danville.\n<ref name=\"boyle\">{{cite web|url=http://transportation.ky.gov/progmgmt/06_syp/html/Boyle.htm |title=Kentucky Transportation Cabinet Six year highway plan for Boyle County |accessdate=2008-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410223610/http://transportation.ky.gov/progmgmt/06_syp/html/Boyle.htm |archivedate=2009-04-10 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kentuckyroads.com/ky_34/ Kentucky Roads - KY 34]\n* [http://transportation.ky.gov/planning/reports/SPRS_listings/listings/boyle.pdf State Primary Road System in Boyle County]\n* [http://transportation.ky.gov/planning/reports/SPRS_listings/listings/garrard.pdf State Primary Road System in Garrard County]\n\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n\n{{Kentucky-road-stub}}\n\n[[Category:State highways in Kentucky|0034]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=KY\n|type=KY\n|route=34\n|maint=[[Kentucky Transportation Cabinet|KYTC]]\n|alternate_name=\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=240|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Kentucky Route 34}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=KY 34 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=21.828\n|length_round=3\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"ktc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planning.kytc.ky.gov/data_reports.asp |title=Kentucky Transportation Cabinet - Division of Planning |accessdate=2008-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070430064216/http://www.planning.kytc.ky.gov/data_reports.asp |archivedate=2007-04-30 }}</ref>\n|established=\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=KY|US|68|KY|52}} near [[Mitchellsburg, Kentucky|Mitchellsburg]]\n|junction=\n{{Jct|state=KY|KY|300}} in [[Parksville, Kentucky|Parksville]]<br>\n{{Jct|state=KY|US-Byp|127|US-Byp|150}} west of [[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]]<br>\n{{Jct|state=KY|US|150|KY|52}} in Danville<br>\n{{Jct|state=KY|US|127}} in Danville<br>\n{{Jct|state=KY|US|27}} east of Danville\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b=Lexington Road east of [[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]]\n|counties=[[Boyle County, Kentucky|Boyle]], [[Garrard County, Kentucky|Garrard]]\n|previous_type=KY\n|previous_route=33\n|next_type=KY\n|next_route=35\n}}\n'''Kentucky Route 34''' ('''KY 34''') is a {{convert|21.828|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}}, east&ndash;west, 2-lane, [[state highway]] in [[Kentucky]] managed by the [[Kentucky Transportation Cabinet]].\n\nKY 34 begins at [[US 68]] and [[KY 52]] near [[Mitchellsburg, Kentucky|Mitchellsburg]] and goes though [[Boyle County, Kentucky|Boyle]] and [[Garrard County, Kentucky|Garrard]] counties before terminating at Lexington Road (Old US 27) east of [[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]] just beyond [[US 27]]. KY 34 formerly terminated at US 27 before US 27 was rebuilt to the west.  It serves as a primary connector between Danville and [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]].\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|state=KY|length_ref=<ref name=\"ktc\"/>}}\n{{KYint\n|county=Boyle\n|cspan=16\n|location=none\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|68|name1=[[KY 52]]<!--not signed here-->}}\n}}\n{{KYint\n|location=Brumfield\n|mile=1.223\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1894|dir1=north|name1=Brumfield Road}}\n|notes=former US 68 east\n}}\n{{KYint\n|location=Mitchellsburg\n|lspan=2\n|mile=3.024\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1856|name1=Scrubgrass Road}}\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=3.273\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1108|dir1=south|name1=Mitchellsburg Knob Road}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of KY 1108\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|location=Parksville\n|lspan=2\n|mile=6.115\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1822|dir1=south|name1=Johnson Branch Road|road=Harberson Lane}}\n|notes=West end of KY 1822 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=6.298\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|300|dir1=east|name1=Alum Springs Road<!--is this a current street name?-->}}\n|notes=Western terminus of KY 300\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|location=none\n|mile=7.207\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1822|dir1=north|name1=Parksville Cross Pike<!--is this a current street name?-->}}\n|notes=east end of KY 1822 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|location=Danville\n|lspan=9\n|mile=12.262\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US-Byp|127|dab1=Danville|US-Byp|150|dab2=Danville}}\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=13.629\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|150|dir1=west|KY|52|dir2=west|name2=Perryville Road}}\n|notes=West end of US 150 / KY 52 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=13.893\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|127|dir1=north|name1=Maple Avenue}}\n|notes=West end of US 127 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|127|dir1=south|name1=South 4th Street}}\n|notes=east end of US 127 south overlap (eastbound)\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=14.469\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|33|dir1=north|name1=North 3rd Street}}\n|notes=East end of US 127 north overlap (westbound)\n}}\n{{KYint\n|type=concur\n|mile=14.801\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|150|dir1=east|KY|52|dir2=east|name2=Stanford Avenue}}\n|notes=East end of US 150 / KY 52 overlap\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=15.063\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|2324|dir1=west|name1=East Lexington Avenue}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of KY 2324\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=16.541\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|1805|dir1=south|name1=Goggin Lane}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of KY 1805\n}}\n{{KYint\n|mile=16.703\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|KY|2168|dir1=west}}<!--anything signed here?-->\n|notes=Eastern terminus of KY 2168\n}}\n{{KYint\n|county=Garrard\n|cspan=2\n|location=none\n|mile=21.705\n|road={{Jct|state=KY|US|27|city1=Lexington|city2=Lancaster}}\n}}\n{{KYint\n|location=none\n|mile=21.828\n|road=Camp Dick Road\n|notes=former US 27\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n\n==Alternate names==\nKY 34 has other names along its path:\n*'''Lebanon Road''' from its western terminus into Danville.\n*'''Main Street''' ([[US 150]] and [[US 127]]) in Danville\n*'''Wilderness Road''' in Danville\n*'''Lexington Road''' from Danville to the Garrard County line\n*'''Chenault Bridge Road''' in Garrard County\n\n==Future==\n{{update|date=November 2014}}\nA new route (KY 2168) is planned to connect KY 34 and KY 33 northeast of Danville.\n<ref name=\"boyle\">{{cite web|url=http://transportation.ky.gov/progmgmt/06_syp/html/Boyle.htm |title=Kentucky Transportation Cabinet Six year highway plan for Boyle County |accessdate=2008-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410223610/http://transportation.ky.gov/progmgmt/06_syp/html/Boyle.htm |archivedate=2009-04-10 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kentuckyroads.com/ky_34/ Kentucky Roads - KY 34]\n* [http://transportation.ky.gov/planning/reports/SPRS_listings/listings/boyle.pdf State Primary Road System in Boyle County]\n* [http://transportation.ky.gov/planning/reports/SPRS_listings/listings/garrard.pdf State Primary Road System in Garrard County]\n\n{{Attached KML|di